# DFlash governor / autotuner

**Task:** #108
**Status:** DEFERRED — design only, replaces today's env-var zoo
**Owner:** TBD
**Date opened:** 2026-04-26

## Background

Today's DFlash configuration surface is an environment-variable zoo
that the user has to set manually:

| Knob | Range | Cost to switch |
|---|---|---|
| `dflash_mode` | on / off | ~1 cycle (drop draft) |
| `block_size` (B) | 8-16 | already adaptive (commit c8b2724) |
| `kv_cache` | asym3 / asym4 / Q8 | LOAD-time only — can't hot-swap |
| `dflash_ngram_block` | on / off | per-cycle (verify-path gate) |
| `loop_break` mode | stop / escalate / temp | per-cycle |
| `cask_sidecar` + `cask_budget` + β | varies | per-cycle (sidecar load is one-time) |
| `repeat_penalty` | 1.0–1.3 | per-cycle, host-path forced when ≠ 1.0 |
| `prompt_normalize` | on / off | LOAD-time |
| `thinking` | on / off (chatml only) | LOAD-time |
| ChainedNgramCache `n` + `min_count` | 2-8 | per-session (#107) |

For end-users this is unusable. Even for power users it's hard to
remember which knob to flip when output starts looping or τ
degrades. **The fix isn't documentation — it's a controller that
watches the signals we already track and toggles the cheap knobs
automatically.** End-user surface collapses to `--mode {auto, fast, safe}`.

## Goal

Replace per-cycle env vars with a state-machine controller. User
sets `--mode auto` (default), governor watches τ + accept_rate +
window-hash + chain-hit-rate signals every cycle, transitions
between {NORMAL, DEGENERATING, RECOVERING, LOOPING} states, and
toggles the cheap knobs (ngram_block, loop_break, B size, RP, chained
ngram) per state.

Acceptance criteria:
- `--mode auto` matches or beats hand-tuned env-var configurations on
  the canonical workload mix (LRU / merge_sort / prose / instruction)
  without per-prompt tuning
- End-user surface area: only `--mode {auto, fast, safe}` exposed by
  default; existing env vars remain as overrides for power users
- No measurable regression on production prompts (humaneval, merge_sort)
  in NORMAL state — governor overhead must be ~ns per cycle

## Two gear-shift levels

### 1. Per-cycle (real-time): controller in spec_step_dflash

State machine with four states + per-state policy:

| State | Entry condition | Active policy |
|---|---|---|
| **NORMAL** | τ_window ≥ 8 AND no window-hash hits in last K | full B=16, no ngram_block, no loop-break, RP=1.0 |
| **DEGENERATING** | τ_window < 4 for 5+ cycles | enable ngram_block, escalate mode, B=12, RP=1.05 |
| **RECOVERING** | τ_window > 6 for 3+ cycles after DEGENERATING | drop ngram_block, ramp B back to 16 over 3 cycles, RP→1.0 |
| **LOOPING** | 3+ window-hash hits in last 16 cycles | hard-stop (synthetic EOS) OR fall back to AR for next 50 tokens |

Transitions are unidirectional except RECOVERING → NORMAL (after a
hysteresis window). LOOPING is terminal for the current generation —
the governor doesn't try to escape; it cleans up.

Signals (all already collected today):
- `tau_window_avg` — rolling τ over last 8 cycles, cheap (single divide)
- `accept_rate_window` — `accepted / (cycles × (B-1))` over last 8
- `window_hash_hits` — already in HIPFIRE_DFLASH_LOOP_BREAK detector
- `chain_hit_rate` — when ChainedNgramCache (#107) is integrated, fraction of chain predictions accepted

Cost: rolling counters + state-machine transition checks per cycle =
microseconds. Negligible vs ~5 ms per spec_step cycle.

### 2. Per-request (gear-shift): prompt classifier at load time

Before the first cycle, classify the prompt and pre-commit to:
- `budget + β` → eviction frequency target (rare for short prompts,
  frequent for long-ctx)
- `kv_cache` mode (this is LOAD-time so can't hot-swap)
- Initial state: NORMAL vs SUSPICIOUS (prompts that historically loop
  start in DEGENERATING-light mode)

Classifier features (all cheap, computed on tokenized prompt):
- Token count (bucketed: <500, 500-2k, 2k-8k, 8k+)
- Token-class ratios: code chars (`(` `)` `{` `}` indent), prose
  whitespace runs (`\n\n`), ChatML markers
- Vocab diversity in prompt (unique-token-ratio over first 256)
- Prompt-fingerprint hash → look up "what config worked best last
  time we saw this fingerprint shape" (the autotuner learns)

Output: a `RequestPolicy` struct passed into spec_step_dflash that
seeds the governor's initial state and decides static knobs.

## Architecture sketch

### `DflashGovernor` struct (spec_step_dflash module)

```rust
pub enum GovernorState {
    Normal,
    Degenerating { cycles_in_state: u32 },
    Recovering { cycles_in_state: u32, baseline_tau: f32 },
    Looping,
}

pub struct DflashGovernor {
    state: GovernorState,
    tau_window: VecDeque<f32>,           // last 8
    accept_window: VecDeque<f32>,        // last 8
    window_hash_hits_recent: u32,        // last 16 cycles
    chain_hit_rate_recent: f32,          // when chained-ngram active
    window_hashes: HashSet<u64>,         // shared with loop-break detector

    // Output policy (consumed by spec_step_dflash each cycle)
    pub current_policy: CyclePolicy,
}

pub struct CyclePolicy {
    pub block_size: usize,
    pub repeat_penalty: f32,
    pub ngram_block: bool,
    pub loop_break_mode: LoopBreakMode,  // none | escalate | stop
    pub fall_back_to_ar: bool,
}

impl DflashGovernor {
    pub fn observe(&mut self, cycle: &SpecStepResult, emitted_tail_hash: u64) {
        // 1. Update rolling windows
        // 2. Check window-hash hits
        // 3. Compute new state via state-transition table
        // 4. Update self.current_policy from state
    }
}
```

### `RequestPolicy` (computed at load-time)

```rust
pub struct RequestPolicy {
    pub initial_state: GovernorState,    // NORMAL | SUSPICIOUS
    pub budget: usize,                   // sidecar budget target
    pub beta: usize,
    pub kv_mode: KvMode,                 // already exists
    pub chained_ngram_n: Option<usize>,  // 0 = off, n=4 default for chat
    pub fingerprint: u64,                // for cache-hit telemetry
}

impl RequestPolicy {
    pub fn classify(prompt_tokens: &[u32], history: Option<&FingerprintCache>) -> Self {
        // Cheap features → choose policy
    }
}
```

### Fingerprint cache (long-term)

Persisted per-user table:
```
fingerprint hash → { best_policy, sample_count, mean_tau, last_used }
```

On cache hit: use best_policy directly. On miss: compute heuristic
classifier policy, record post-generation outcome. Over a coding
agent's lifetime, ~80% of requests hit cache after a week.

Storage: `~/.hipfire/governor-cache.json`, ~10 KB per ~100 entries.

## End-user surface

Today's CLI:
```
hipfire run qwen3.5:9b "..."
HIPFIRE_DFLASH_LOOP_BREAK=stop \
HIPFIRE_DFLASH_NGRAM_BLOCK=1 \
HIPFIRE_DFLASH_CHAINED_NGRAM_N=4 \
hipfire run qwen3.5:9b "..."  # power user
```

Proposed:
```
hipfire run qwen3.5:9b "..."                  # auto (default)
hipfire run --mode fast qwen3.5:9b "..."      # disable all guards, max speed
hipfire run --mode safe qwen3.5:9b "..."      # eager guards (always-on)
HIPFIRE_DFLASH_NGRAM_BLOCK=1 hipfire run ...  # power-user override still works
```

`--mode auto`: governor controls everything per cycle.
`--mode fast`: governor disabled, all guards off (current default
when no env vars set). For benchmarking and trusted prompts.
`--mode safe`: all guards always on. For unknown prompts in production
where conservative behavior beats peak speed.

## Implementation phases

### Phase 1: Per-cycle governor (~300 lines)

- New `DflashGovernor` struct in `engine/src/speculative.rs`
- Plumb signal collection into spec_step_dflash (rolling τ, accept,
  window-hash count) — all already computed, just need to thread
  them out
- `CyclePolicy` consumed by spec_step_dflash to gate the existing
  knobs (replaces direct env-var reads)
- Env-gate behind `HIPFIRE_DFLASH_GOVERNOR=1` initially, default OFF
  (no behavior change). Promote to default after benching.

### Phase 2: Prompt classifier (~150 lines)

- `RequestPolicy::classify` impl with feature extraction
- Hand-tuned heuristic mapping (code → budget=8k+β=2k, prose → 16k+2k,
  chat → 4k+1k)
- No fingerprint cache yet — just deterministic from features

### Phase 3: Fingerprint cache (~200 lines)

- Persistent JSON store at `~/.hipfire/governor-cache.json`
- Update mechanic: post-generation, record actual τ + tok/s, blend
  into table entry
- Eviction: LRU at 1000 entries

### Phase 4: CLI surface (~80 lines)

- `--mode {auto, fast, safe}` flag on `run` and `serve`
- `auto` enables governor + classifier + fingerprint cache
- Existing env vars remain as overrides

## Bench plan

For each phase, compare against:
- Current default (no env vars set, all guards off)
- Hand-tuned-per-workload (the env-var combo we'd manually pick)

Workloads:
- humaneval (no governor effect expected — NORMAL state throughout)
- merge_sort (no effect — also NORMAL)
- LRU class with max=2000 (governor should detect loop early, transition
  to LOOPING, hard-stop within 5-10 cycles of degeneration)
- Multi-turn chat with deliberate repetitive prompts
- Mixed-length prompt batch (validates classifier)

Acceptance for Phase 1: governor matches or beats best hand-tuned
per-workload by ≥ 5% mean tok/s, while reducing user-visible config
to a single flag.

## Risk

- **State-machine oscillation**: poorly-tuned hysteresis could
  flip-flop between NORMAL and DEGENERATING. Mitigation: minimum
  cycles-in-state thresholds (already in design), well-tested
  transition table.
- **Wrong-classifier penalty**: if the prompt-fingerprint cache
  associates a workload with a bad config, future generations
  inherit the penalty. Mitigation: blend with default heuristic at
  low sample counts; explicit cache-bust command.
- **Telemetry leak**: fingerprint cache stores prompt hashes — these
  are not the prompt text but could correlate. Mitigation: opt-in
  via `--mode auto`, opt-out via `HIPFIRE_NO_FINGERPRINT_CACHE=1`,
  document clearly in privacy notes.
- **Maintenance cost**: state machines are hard to debug and easy to
  ossify. Plan: per-state telemetry exposed via `--mode auto --debug`
  showing transitions + signal values per cycle, so misbehavior is
  visible.

## Out of scope

- Hot-swap of `kv_cache` (impossible without re-loading model)
- Hot-swap of `prompt_normalize` (LOAD-time)
- Hot-swap of `thinking` mode (LOAD-time)
- ML-based classifier (deterministic heuristic + fingerprint cache
  is enough for now; ML adds latency + maintenance)

## Why deferred

- Phase 1 alone is ~300 lines + a state machine + a controller
  interface. Solid week of focused work to do well.
- Current operational surface (env vars) works for the limited number
  of users we have. Investment in `--mode auto` makes sense once we
  have user complaints about the env-var zoo.
- ChainedNgramCache integration (#107) lands first — its chain-hit-rate
  signal is one of the governor's inputs. Without it, governor is
  watching one fewer signal.

## Triggers to un-defer

- User/CI complaints about env-var config burden
- ChainedNgramCache integration (#107) ships and we want to compose
- Multi-tenant serve daemon needs per-request adaptive config (each
  client has different workload shape)
- Telemetry shows some prompts loop-spiral while others run clean —
  the governor catches the difference automatically

